   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>News Roundup:</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>By the Second Stringers</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Kohath</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">05/20/2002 10:50 PM CDT &nbsp;&nbsp; 9 Comments</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText"><big>&quot;I am the Pirate King.  It is, it is, a Glorious Thing...&quot;</big><p>You've probably already seen it, but Nadia from <a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis">the Brell Serilis board</a> posted a link to <a href="http://www.gamespy.com/interviews/may02/eq2/">the Gamespy interview with Bill Trost</a>.  Of all the guys involved in the creation of EverQuest, Bill Trost is one of the quietest (at least as far as the public is concerned), as well as being one of the most important.  He's being interviewed because he's the Lead Game Designer behind EQ II.<p>Despite the terrible interview questions, the Gamespy piece still manages to be interesting.  First, there are six very impressive new EQ2 screenshots.  Second, we learn a few new things about EQ2 that we haven't heard before.  Specifically, this bit about regions seems to be new:<p><b>The regions of EverQuest II are going to be substantially larger that the zones of EverQuest and load times are going to be greatly reduced as well as being less frequent.</b><p>Reading between the lines, it seems clear that the &quot;regions&quot; in EQ2 are based on a somewhat different concept than EverQuest's zones.<p>We also learn that EQ2's quests can have a lasting effect on the world, that there's 38 people on the EQ2 team, and that Mr. Trost secretly relishes the life of a high-seas pirate.<p><big>&quot;And the Console-ation Prize Goes To...&quot;</big><p>Rod Humble was <a href="http://gamespot.com/gamespot/stories/previews/0,10869,2866016,00.html/">also interviewed</a> over the weekend, this time by Gamespot on the subject of EverQuest Online Adventures for the PS2.  This interview is much less interesting -- mostly because none of us at Mobhunter will ever end up playing the upcoming console title.<p><big>The Legend of the Missing Keys</big><p>In other news, Scott Hartsman <a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showMessage?topicID=16626.topic">recently addressed</a> the lack of a decent keyring in the game.  It seems it's one of those issues that's easy to describe, but hard to fix in the code.<p>And the many, many holders of those keys on the Stormhammer server have come into such a conflict that the Legends staff has implemented <a href="http://legends.everquest.station.sony.com/newsview.jsp?o=43132">a reservation service</a> for slow-spawning uber-content.  I think everyone is surprised it took this long.<p><big>Tempest in a Teapot</big><p>There was much ado this weekend about EverQuest's <a href="http://eqlive.station.sony.com/news_section/newsview.jsp?story=43093">Weekend of War</a>.  The thing is, I never saw any evidence of any kind of war.  Back in my day, when we had a war, you'd hear about it -- what with all the fighting and such.  Anyone care to let us in on what happened?  Did we win?  The Shamen <a href="http://forums.interealms.com/shaman/showthread.php?threadid=1792">report</a> that, mostly, we lost.<p><big>&quot;E-3? You Sunk My ... Oh, Nevermind.&quot;</big><p>This week is E3, so expect to be teased with lots of info about games you can't play yet.  Blizzard, for example, <a href="http://www.blizzard.com/press/020520wow.shtml">has announced</a> that they'll be showing World of Warcraft.<p>Star Wars Galaxies is <a href="http://www.lucasarts.com/products/galaxies/">going to be made</a> for the PS2 and the X-box.  Incidentally, Star Wars Galaxies is also listed to work in the <a href="http://www.matrox.com/mga/products/parhelia512/technology/surround_gaming.cfm">surround gaming mode</a> of that new Matrox Parhelia video card.  After <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B000067FDY/mobhunter-20">pre-ordering SWG</a>, some of you might want to learn some marketable skills, get jobs, and save up to pay for this setup.  You have a few months yet.<p><big>End of News</big><p>Absor hasn't said anything interesting for several days now.  With Moorgard away, me and Csenicier sick, and half the other EQ-site staffs at E3, this is going to be an unusual week of news.  If you find anything interesting, <a href="mailto:kohath@mobhunter.com">send it to me</a>.  I'm not as good at writing these as Moorgard, but honestly where else are you going to go?<br></font>
  </td>
 </tr>
